df-cnf
blocks.content: Define the Cantor normal form function, which takes as input a finitely supported function from ` y ` to ` x ` and outputs the corresponding member of the ordinal exponential ` x ^o y ` . The content of the original Cantor Normal Form theorem is that for ` x = _om ` this function is a bijection onto ` _om ^o y ` for any ordinal ` y ` (or, since the function restricts naturally to different ordinals, the statement that the composite function is a bijection to ` On ` ). More can be said about the function, however, and in particular it is an order isomorphism for a certain easily defined well-ordering of the finitely supported functions, which gives an alternate definition ~ cantnffval2 of this function in terms of ~ df-oi . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 25-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 28-Jun-2019.)

blocks.name: cantnfs
blocks.content: Elementhood in the set of finitely supported functions from ` B ` to ` A ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 25-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 28-Jun-2019.)

thm cantnfs(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wb(wcel(c0, c1), wa(wf(c0, c2, c3), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls))))
  -| wceq(c1, cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c2)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, con0))
} = {
  bitrd(w0, wcel(c0, c1), wa(wf(c0, c2, c3), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls)), wa(wcel(c0, co(c3, cmap, c2)), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls)))
  syl6bb(w0, wcel(c0, c1), wa(wcel(c0, co(c3, cmap, c2)), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls)), wcel(c0, crab(hs0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls))))
  eleq2d(c0, c1, crab(hs0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls)), w0)
  syl5eq(c1, crab(hs0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls)), cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c2)), w0)
  cantnfdm(hs0, c3, c2, crab(hs0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls)), w0)
  eqid(crab(hs0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls)))
  elrab(hs0, c0, co(c3, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(hs0), cfsupp, emptycls), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls))
  breq1(cv(hs0), c0, cfsupp, emptycls)
  anbi1d(w0, wcel(c0, co(c3, cmap, c2)), wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls), wf(c0, c2, c3))
  elmapd(c0, c3, c2, con0, con0, w0)
  diff.hs0.c(c3)
  diff.hs0.c(c2)
  diff.hs0.c(c0)
  diff.hs0.c(co(c3, cmap, c2))
  diff.hs0.w(wbr(c0, cfsupp, emptycls))
}

thm cantnfcl(class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, wff w0) {

} = {
  jca(w0, wwe(cep, co(c0, csupp, emptycls)), wcel(cdm(c1), com))

  ovexd(c0, csupp, emptycls, w0)
  mpisyl(w0, wwe(cep, co(c0, csupp, emptycls)), wss(co(c0, csupp, emptycls), con0), wwe(cep, con0))
  sstrd(co(c0, csupp, emptycls), con0, c4, w0)

blocks.name: cantnfle
blocks.content: A lower bound on the ` CNF ` function. Since ` ( ( A CNF B ) `` F ) ` is defined as the sum of ` ( A ^o x ) .o ( F `` x ) ` over all ` x ` in the support of ` F ` , it is larger than any of these terms (and all other terms are zero, so we can extend the statement to all ` C e. B ` instead of just those ` C ` in the support). (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 28-Jun-2019.)

blocks.name: cantnflt
blocks.content: An upper bound on the partial sums of the ` CNF ` function. Since each term dominates all previous terms, by induction we can bound the whole sum with any exponent ` A ^o C ` where ` C ` is larger than any exponent ` ( G `` x ) , x e. K ` which has been summed so far. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 29-Jun-2019.)

blocks.name: cantnfp1
blocks.content: If ` F ` is created by adding a single term ` ( F `` X ) = Y ` to ` G ` , where ` X ` is larger than any element of the support of ` G ` , then ` F ` is also a finitely supported function and it is assigned the value ` ( ( A ^o X ) .o Y ) +o z ` where ` z ` is the value of ` G ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 1-Jul-2019.)

blocks.name: cantnflem1
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ cantnf . This part of the proof is showing uniqueness of the Cantor normal form. We already know that the relation ` T ` is a strict order, but we haven't shown it is a well-order yet. But being a strict order is enough to show that two distinct ` F , G ` are ` T ` -related as ` F < G ` or ` G < F ` , and WLOG assuming that ` F < G ` , we show that ` CNF ` respects this order and maps these two to different ordinals. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 2-Jul-2019.)

blocks.name: cantnflem3
blocks.content: Lemma for ~ cantnf . Here we show existence of Cantor normal forms. Assuming (by transfinite induction) that every number less than ` C ` has a normal form, we can use ~ oeeu to factor ` C ` into the form ` ( ( A ^o X ) .o Y ) +o Z ` where ` 0 < Y < A ` and ` Z < ( A ^o X ) ` (and a fortiori ` X < B ` ). Then since ` Z < ( A ^o X ) <_ ( A ^o X ) .o Y <_ C ` , ` Z ` has a normal form, and by appending the term ` ( A ^o X ) .o Y ` using ~ cantnfp1 we get a normal form for ` C ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.)

blocks.name: cantnf
blocks.content: The Cantor Normal Form theorem. The function ` ( A CNF B ) ` , which maps a finitely supported function from ` B ` to ` A ` to the sum ` ( ( A ^o f ( a 1 ) ) o. a 1 ) +o ` ` ( ( A ^o f ( a 2 ) ) o. a 2 ) +o ... ` over all indices ` a < B ` such that ` f ( a ) ` is nonzero, is an order isomorphism from the ordering ` T ` of finitely supported functions to the set ` ( A ^o B ) ` under the natural order. Setting ` A = _om ` and letting ` B ` be arbitrarily large, the surjectivity of this function implies that every ordinal has a Cantor normal form (and injectivity, together with coherence ~ cantnfres , implies that such a representation is unique). (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.)

blocks.name: oemapwe
blocks.content: The lexicographic order on a function space of ordinals gives a well-ordering with order type equal to the ordinal exponential. This provides an alternate definition of the ordinal exponential. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.)
blocks.origin:
thm oemapwe(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wa(wwe(c0, c1), wceq(cdm(coi(c0, c1)), co(c2, coe, c3))))
  -| wceq(c1, cdm(co(c2, ccnf, c3)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, con0))
  -| wceq(c0, copab(s0, s1, wrex(s2, c3, wa(wcel(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s2)), cfv(cv(s1), cv(s2))), wral(s3, c3, wi(wcel(cv(s2), cv(s3)), wceq(cfv(cv(s0), cv(s3)), cfv(cv(s1), cv(s3)))))))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)
  -| diffss(s1, s2)
  -| diffss(s1, s3)
  -| diffss(s2, s3)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c3)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c3)
  -| diffsc(s2, c1)
  -| diffsc(s2, c2)
  -| diffsc(s2, c3)
  -| diffsc(s3, c2)
  -| diffsc(s3, c3)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
  -| diffsw(s1, w0)
  -| diffsw(s2, w0)
} = {
  jca(w0, wwe(c0, c1), wceq(cdm(coi(c0, c1)), co(c2, coe, c3)))
  eqcomd(cdm(coi(c0, c1)), co(c2, coe, c3), w0)
  simpld(w0, wceq(co(c2, coe, c3), cdm(coi(c0, c1))), wceq(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), coi(c0, c1)))
  mpbi2and(w0, wa(wceq(co(c2, coe, c3), cdm(coi(c0, c1))), wceq(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), coi(c0, c1))), word(co(c2, coe, c3)), wiso(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), cep, c0, co(c2, coe, c3), c1))
  syl(w0, word(co(c2, coe, c3)), wcel(co(c2, coe, c3), con0))
  syl(w0, wiso(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), cep, c0, co(c2, coe, c3), c1), wiso(co(c2, ccnf, c3), c0, cep, c1, co(c2, coe, c3)))
  isocnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3), c0, cep, c1, co(c2, coe, c3))
  sylancl(w0, wb(wa(word(co(c2, coe, c3)), wiso(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), cep, c0, co(c2, coe, c3), c1)), wa(wceq(co(c2, coe, c3), cdm(coi(c0, c1))), wceq(ccnv(co(c2, ccnf, c3)), coi(c0, c1)))), wwe(c0, c1), wse(c0, c1))
  mpbird(w0, wwe(c0, c1), wwe(cep, co(c2, coe, c3)))
  3syl(w0, wwe(cep, co(c2, coe, c3)), wcel(co(c2, coe, c3), con0), word(co(c2, coe, c3)))

  oecl(c2, c3)

  ordwe(co(c2, coe, c3))

  cantnf(s0, s1, s2, s3, c2, c3, c0, c1, w0)

  ax-mp(wse(c0, c1), wcel(c1, universe))

blocks.name: oef1o
blocks.content: A bijection of the base sets induces a bijection on ordinal exponentials. (The assumption ` ( F `` (/) ) = (/) ` can be discharged using ~ fveqf1o .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 30-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 3-Jul-2019.)

thm oef1o(setvar s0, setvar s1, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wf1o(c0, co(c1, coe, c2), co(c3, coe, c4)))
  -| wi(w0, wf1o(c5, c1, c3))
  -| wi(w0, wf1o(c6, c2, c4))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, cdif(con0, c1o)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c2, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c3, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c4, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wceq(cfv(c5, emptycls), emptycls))
  -| wceq(c7, cmpt(s0, crab(s1, co(c1, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(s1), cfsupp, emptycls)), ccom(c5, ccom(cv(s0), ccnv(c6)))))
  -| wceq(c0, ccom(ccom(co(c3, ccnf, c4), c7), ccnv(co(c1, ccnf, c2))))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c1)
  -| diffsc(s0, c2)
  -| diffsc(s0, c3)
  -| diffsc(s0, c4)
  -| diffsc(s0, c5)
  -| diffsc(s0, c6)
  -| diffsc(s1, c1)
  -| diffsc(s1, c2)
  -| diffsc(s1, c3)
  -| diffsc(s1, c4)
  -| diffsc(s1, c5)
  -| diffsc(s1, c6)
  -| diffsw(s0, w0)
  -| diffsw(s1, w0)
} = {
  sylibr(w0, wf1o(c0, co(c1, coe, c2), co(c3, coe, c4)), wf1o(ccom(ccom(co(c3, ccnf, c4), c7), ccnv(co(c1, ccnf, c2))), co(c1, coe, c2), co(c3, coe, c4)))
  syl2anc(w0, wf1o(ccom(ccom(co(c3, ccnf, c4), c7), ccnv(co(c1, ccnf, c2))), co(c1, coe, c2), co(c3, coe, c4)), wf1o(ccom(co(c3, ccnf, c4), c7), cdm(co(c1, ccnf, c2)), co(c3, coe, c4)), wf1o(ccnv(co(c1, ccnf, c2)), co(c1, coe, c2), cdm(co(c1, ccnf, c2))))
  syl2anc(w0, wf1o(ccom(co(c3, ccnf, c4), c7), cdm(co(c1, ccnf, c2)), co(c3, coe, c4)), wf1o(co(c3, ccnf, c4), cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4)), co(c3, coe, c4)), wf1o(c7, cdm(co(c1, ccnf, c2)), cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4))))
  cantnff1o(c3, c4, cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4)), w0)
  eqid(cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4)))
  mpbird(w0, wf1o(c7, cdm(co(c1, ccnf, c2)), cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4))), wf1o(c7, crab(s1, co(c1, cmap, c2), wbr(cv(s1), cfsupp, emptycls)), cdm(co(c3, ccnf, c4))))

blocks.name: cnfcom
blocks.content: Any ordinal ` B ` is equinumerous to the leading term of its Cantor normal form. Here we show that bijection explicitly. (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 30-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 3-Jul-2019.)
blocks.origin:
thm cnfcom(setvar s0, setvar s1, setvar s2, setvar s3, class c0, class c1, class c2, class c3, class c4, class c5, class c6, class c7, class c8, class c9, wff w0) {
  |- wi(w0, wf1o(cfv(c0, csuc(c1)), cfv(c2, csuc(c1)), co(co(com, coe, cfv(c3, c1)), comu, cfv(c4, cfv(c3, c1)))))
  -| wceq(c5, cdm(co(com, ccnf, c6)))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c6, con0))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c7, co(com, coe, c6)))
  -| wceq(c4, cfv(ccnv(co(com, ccnf, c6)), c7))
  -| wceq(c3, coi(cep, co(c4, csupp, emptycls)))
  -| wceq(c2, cseqom(cmpo(s0, s1, universe, universe, co(c8, coa, cv(s1))), emptycls))
  -| wceq(c0, cseqom(cmpo(s0, s2, universe, universe, c9), emptycls))
  -| wceq(c8, co(co(com, coe, cfv(c3, cv(s0))), comu, cfv(c4, cfv(c3, cv(s0)))))
  -| wceq(c9, cun(cmpt(s3, c8, co(cdm(cv(s2)), coa, cv(s3))), ccnv(cmpt(s3, cdm(cv(s2)), co(c8, coa, cv(s3))))))
  -| wi(w0, wcel(c1, cdm(c3)))
  -| diffss(s0, s1)
  -| diffss(s0, s2)
  -| diffss(s0, s3)

blocks.name: cnfcom3
blocks.content: Any infinite ordinal ` B ` is equinumerous to a power of ` _om ` . (We are being careful here to show explicit bijections rather than simple equinumerosity because we want a uniform construction for ~ cnfcom3c .) (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 28-May-2015.) (Revised by AV, 4-Jul-2019.)

blocks.name: cnfcom3c
blocks.content: Wrap the construction of ~ cnfcom3 into an existential quantifier. For any ` _om C_ b ` , there is a bijection from ` b ` to some power of ` _om ` . Furthermore, this bijection is _canonical_ , which means that we can find a single function ` g ` which will give such bijections for every ` b ` less than some arbitrarily large bound ` A ` . (Contributed by Mario Carneiro, 30-May-2015.)
